Home About Research Careers Blog Research at Adept In the past decade, progress in AI and its societal and economic impact have been propelled largely by advances in neural Innovations in deep learning from years of industrial and academic R&D underpin a multitude of useful technologies such as translation, protein folding, , and programming Impressive increases in scale combined with simple training techniques now endow a single model with remarkable competence in several tasks, a departure from the bespoke deep learning models of the past that were engineered for specific â Adept is building generally intelligent natural language interfaces to the digital world, empowering people to interact with machines just like they would with a At the heart of this partnership lie some of the most exciting research challenges in â We believe that many of the important research problems on the path to building generally intelligent interfaces can only be accessed with real people using our models and improving them with To act in the digital world at the usersâ behest, our models need several skills: They need to process large amount of contextual information, Understand and manipulate multimodal information, Learn from user feedback, Teach themselves how to use software tools with limited human At Adept, you will be working with some of the leading researchers in areas such as modeling, systems, reinforcement learning from human feedback, data curation, and user As we build useful products out of capabilities that are already within grasp, our fundamental research will unlock the next tier of capabilities that will further empower We have the rare privilege of shaping how people will interact with the digital world and we are looking for passionate and brilliant minds to join us on this â Relevant Research Unified Scaling Laws for Routed Language Models Read More Training Large Language Models Read More Scaling Local for Parameter Efficient Visual Backbones Read More Show Your Work: Scratchpads for Intermediate Computation with Language Models Read More Scaling Language Models: Methods, Analysis & Insights from Training Gopher Read More Program Synthesis with Large Language Models Read More Improving language models by retrieving from trillions of tokens Read More Conformer: transformer for speech recognition Read More in Home About Research Careers Blog Adept Useful General Intelligence Twitter LinkedIn   : Transformer for Actions Hello! Home About Research Careers Blog : Transformer for Actions September , AI has moved at an incredible pace in the last few Scaling up Transformers has led to remarkable capabilities in language (e.g., , PaLM, Chinchilla), code (e.g., Codex, AlphaCode), and image generation (e.g., , Imagen). At Adept, we are building the next frontier of models that can take actions in the digital worldâthatâs why weâre excited to introduce our first large model, Action Transformer (ACT-1) . â Why are we so excited about this? â First, we believe the clearest framing of general intelligence is a system that can do anything a human can do in front of a A foundation model for actions, trained to use every software tool, API, and webapp that exists, is a practical path to this ambitious goal, and is our first step in this â Second, the next era of computing will be defined by natural language interfaces that allow us to tell our computers what we want directly, rather than doing it by We hope these snippets of will give you a window into the next frontier of computing as we see it! â Sign up here to join the waitlist for the upcoming alpha release of our first product built around â Capability preview is a Transformer trained to use digital tools â among other things, we recently taught it how to use a web Right now, itâs hooked up to a Chrome extension which allows to observe whatâs happening in the browser and take certain actions, like clicking, typing, and scrolling, The observation is a custom ârenderingâ of the browser viewport thatâs meant to generalize across websites, and the action space is the UI elements available on the â Thereâs a lot of room to make it faster, both on the modeling side and on the software side - so we expect future systems will have latency thatâs largely imperceptible to These videos have been sped up to make them easier for you to An upcoming technical post will go into much more detail on all of these â Here are some cool things can do! â can take a user request and execute The user simply types a command into the text box and does the In this example, this requires repeatedly taking actions and observations over a long time horizon to fulfill a single â â This can be especially powerful for manual tasks and compl

Is Eclipse an optimistic or rollup? What is a modular rollup? What is a data availability layer? What is a settlement layer? What is the timeline for Eclipse? Whatâs a virtual machine (VM)? A virtual machine is a piece of software that can run Specifically, the virtual machine executes smart contracts for a Why do we use the Solana VM? The Solana (Sealevel) virtual machine is a highly parallelized runtime that is constantly For EVM blockchains such as Ethereum or Optimism, at any given point there is only a single program (This is called "single-threaded.") For the Solana VM, if you have multiple cores, you can run several programs at the exact same time, substantially increasing Moreover, the execution layer continues to improve: Seahorse Lang lets you write Solana VM programs in Soon the Solana VM will support Move bytecode The Solana VM has a fee market coming What is a rollup? Is Eclipse an optimistic or rollup? For comparison, a Layer 1 blockchain is a blockchain that does not depend on any other chain for Layer 1 blockchains require that the majority of voting power is A rollup is a type of scaling solution that executes transactions outside of any Layer 1 and later posts the data to a Layer 1 For an optimistic rollup , a "sequencer" executes transactions and posts the result to a Layer 1 along with a A "verifier" can the transactions, and if it disagrees on the result, the verifier can challenge the sequencer via a "settlement " If the verifier is correct, the sequencer loses their bounty and the bounty is awarded to the For a rollup , sequencers execute transactions and generate a "validity proof" (evidence) that they executed the transactions Sequencers must provide this validity proof to the settlement layer for their work to be The validity proof is typically expensive to Eclipse is deploying as an optimistic rollup, but we are working on a rollup in What is a modular rollup? A normal rollup executes transactions but uses the same base layer for settlement, consensus, and data That s a simple design, but it s not good because that base layer is likely not the right choice for all of those A modular rollup separates the functions of a blockchain: (i) execution, (ii) settlement, and (iii) consensus & data In Eclipse s vision for the future of rollups, you could pick any execution layer (ex: EVM, SVM, or Move), choose the right data availability layer for your needs (ex: Ethereum, Celestia, or Amazon Web Services), and settlement could occur somewhere else What is a data availability layer? This question requires some additional A full node in a blockchain network downloads all blocks (transactions) and executes A light node doesn t do that, but a data availability layer enables the light node to efficiently verify that blocks are available to all full nodes on the Data availability is important because storing huge amounts of data limits how decentralized and scalable a blockchain can It would not be possible to build a decentralized Solana VM rollup without this critical Most chains today don t provide data availability because they aren t designed for Celestia, Polygon Avail, and EigenLayer are all data availability layers, and danksharding will bring data availability sampling to Ethereum in the What is a settlement layer? Full nodes every transaction and determine the current state of the What happens when these full nodes disagree? In general, the blockchain will For a blockchain where the majority of nodes are honest, the "fork choice rule" will dictate that the correct chain is whatever the honest nodes For a rollup that does not make the assumption that the majority of nodes are honest, the majority of actors might be As a blockchain user (light node), how do we determine which is the correct fork? A settlement layer is a hub to verify proofs and resolve fraud disputes to determine the "correct" The settlement layer also lets you move tokens between the execution chains (a bridge). What is the timeline for Eclipse? The Eclipse testnet will be available Q1 , and the Eclipse mainnet is targeted for Q2 If you re a major protocol interested in getting early access to Eclipse, reach out to or DM us on Whatâs a virtual machine (VM)? How It Works - Digma Skip to content Why Digma How It Works About Us Blog Contact Us Get Digma Why Digma How It Works About Us Blog Contact Us Get Digma how digma works Raw data and dashboards take time to analyze and slow developers We built Digma to interpret the information collected by observability tools, turn them into insights and integrate those insights with your IDE and dev tools so you can use them while Get Digma Continuous Feedback Pipeline Turns Observability Data Into Insights It takes time and manual work to aggregate and understand the significance of raw observability And though these insights are too valuable to ignore, we know most developers simply don’t have the time (or patience) to root them Digma automates this process, providing a continuous feedback pipeline that analyzes logs, traces and metrics from OpenTelemetry and other observability data sources to glean insights into how your code runs in a Provide Insights In Context Context switching is guaranteed to slow you down, so Digma makes observability insights directly accessible in your With Digma, you can answer questions like these as you work: Where is this function called from? Is anyone using it in production? Is this a problematic area of the code? Where are my bottlenecks? What type of errors does this code raise in runtime? Which issues are escalating? Which ones are affecting the end user? WHY DEVELOPERS NEED DIGMA Context switching is guaranteed to slow you down, so Digma makes observability insights directly accessible in your With Digma, you can answer questions like these as you work: Where is this function called from? Is anyone using it in production? Is this a problematic area of the code? Where are my bottlenecks? What type of errors does this code raise in runtime? Which issues are escalating? Which ones are affecting the end user? WHY DEVELOPERS NEED DIGMA Integrates with your existing Framework Built for OpenTelemetry If you’re already using OpenTelemetry, you just need to add Digma as another target for the observability A single line of code is usually Supported Technologies To use Digma, your coding language and IDE need to be supported as Here are the languages and IDEs we support We are adding to this list as we grow, so if you don’t see your stack represented here, please let us know . CODING LANGUAGES: Python GoLang IDES: Visual Studio Code Jetbrains Rider IDE Frequently Asked Questions Which platforms and stacks do you currently support? Right now, most of the data Digma collects is OpenTelemetry In the future, we will be able to ingest data from other technologies as well, such as eBPF or We have a limited set of language specific components, but for the sake of focus, we currently support over Jetbrains Rider IDE, and GoLang and Python over Visual Studio Support is coming soon for If you’re using other stacks you want to see supported, please let us know – we’re definitely taking your responses into How is Digma different from other observability tools? We don’t compete with any tool existing today because there isn’t any other tool that generates this type of feedback and delivers it in We do work very well together with other tools looking at the same data, like Jaeger and Prometheus, as well as traditional observability tools like Datadog or There are plenty of tools that offer troubleshooting or debugging capabilities after an issue is already identified, or give some raw realtime However, Digma is fundamentally different because we turn raw data into usable insights, and make those insights easily accessible to developers so they can take a proactive (not reactive) approach to Do you have any example applications I can clone? We have a few example applications on Github, and we are working on adding DotNet Sample Application Django Sample Application FastAPI Sample Application Is this going to instrument my code and change it in creepy ways in production? Absolutely not! We rely on the OpenTelemetry vanilla instrumentation with a few added attributes of our We leave your code Can Digma predict code behavior? It uses your production data to generate real insights – not Do I need to make code changes to use Digma? If you’re already using OpenTelemetry, you’re good to If you are not yet using it, we should be a part of your stack if you’re considering adding observability to your code! How do I contribute or get involved? We are committed to making Digma an open source However, we are just getting started, and some of the code is not yet finalized enough to accept Currently, our vsc o de plugin repo is public with an MIT We’ll continue to add the additional repos as they become formalized enough to start working on them If you are interested in being a contributor, drop us a line ! We like to use yarn start to run a local build, especially when we re working with changes that involve links or Style Guidelines ​ Our objective in organizing and creating website content is that anyone who finds their way to any RISC Zero content is able to rapidly find their way to the material suits their In order to achieve this objective, we rely on: Clear Purpose : We aim for docs, and we head each document with a succinct statement of purpose and pointers to related We use roadmaps, signposting, headings, and text formatting to guide the reader s attention toward the purpose of the Keep it Simple : We write short sentences with minimal superflous We keep content digestible by splitting long docs into smaller Progressive Disclosure : Our landing pages are simple and Both at the level of and individual , we present a bird s eye view first with paths toward higher levels of detail and Lots of Pointers : We keep materials succinct through extensive use of pointers on modular, Consistent and Accessible Terminology : We are diligent about using our official terminology as defined and using precise language as much as At the same time, we minimize our use of technical jargon, taking care to provide reference pages to knowledge as Terminology Conventions ​ RISC Zero Official Terminology Our terminology and naming conventions are subject to ongoing evaluation, and we encourage conversation and questions on these Please let us know via a GitHub issue when you encounter terms that don t seem quite Navbar and Sidebars ​ The navbar is defined in . Any changes require manual How to edit the navbar The sidebars are defined in . Any changes outside of docs reference-docs , docs explainers zkp , or docs explainers zkvm require manual How to edit the sidebar The default configuration (and our current configuration) is that pages do not have sidebars and docs Categories of Documentation ​ We organize our docs into 4 categories, as per the Divio documentation guidelines . Reference docs and explainers live on this site under docs reference-docs and docs explainers . Tutorials & guides live on Github in the risc0 rust-starter Reference Docs ​ We typically organize reference docs according to the following sections we use About NTTs as a Topic Topic is used to [concise explanation of relevance to RISC Zero] Documentation Basic Function Content 1 Content 2 Content 3 Suggested Reading Changes to this organization can be proposed for discussion via a GitHub issue or proposed for action via a
